				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225831" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1481761557 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Dec 2016 00:25</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2709609">
									

<p>Interesting. I was just talking about time fuckery the other day. I choose to assume cause.</p>
<p>I can't fully explain why these kinds of tales succeed where a lot of others don't in taking a complex subject that could easily become way too convoluted for its own good and presenting it in an interesting manner. This is also a somewhat rare example of a conversation being meaty enough to merit a tale. Enjoyable, in any event.</p>
<p>If I have one observation, there's flashes here and there of a more literary style than the rest of the tale, namely the semi-narrative asides and the line where Xyank downs his drink. It's not a problem at all here, but I did find myself kind of wanting you to let that element off the chain a little more. Not that the other portions were too dry for my liking, but it was an interesting sensibility that I wouldn't mind seeing more of as this continues to develop.</p>

							</div>

								
					
